#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:653
msgid "Parametrizing conditional raising"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:655
msgid ""
"Use :func:`pytest.raises` with the :ref:`pytest.mark.parametrize ref` "
"decorator to write parametrized tests in which some tests raise exceptions "
"and others do not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:659
msgid ""
"``contextlib.nullcontext`` can be used to test cases that are not expected "
"to raise exceptions but that should result in some value. The value is given "
"as the ``enter_result`` parameter, which will be available as the ``with`` "
"statement’s target (``e`` in the example below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:664
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:666
msgid ""
"from contextlib import nullcontext\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    \"example_input,expectation\",\n"
"    [\n"
"        (3, nullcontext(2)),\n"
"        (2, nullcontext(3)),\n"
"        (1, nullcontext(6)),\n"
"        (0, pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError)),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_division(example_input, expectation):\n"
"    \"\"\"Test how much I know division.\"\"\"\n"
"    with expectation as e:\n"
"        assert (6 / example_input) == e"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:687
msgid ""
"In the example above, the first three test cases should run without any "
"exceptions, while the fourth should raise a ``ZeroDivisionError`` exception, "
"which is expected by pytest."
msgstr ""
